com.ihealth.communication.manager

Class iHealthDevicesManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.ihealth.communication.manager.iHealthDevicesManager

  • public class iHealthDevicesManager
extends java.lang.Object

    iHealth SDK document

    1. the need to introduce the file and related configuration

    Need to introduce the development kit iHealthLibrary.jar. Which are ABI BP3, BP5, BP7, BG1, BG5, BP, HS3, Android4.0 and HS5 support AM3 and its version; AM3S, HS4, and PO3 support Android4.3 and the above version and Android4.4 Samsung brand mobile phone.

    2. standard operating procedures

    (1) Initialization iHealth SDK.
    init(Context)

    (2) Verify iHealth device uses-permission.

    (3) Register callback, and get a callback ID.

    (4) Add callback filter.
    addCallbackFilterForAddress(int, String...) addCallbackFilterForDeviceType(int, String...)

    (5) Discovery a iHealth device.
    iHealthDevicesManager#startDiscovery(int)

    (6) Connection a iHealth device.
    connectDevice(String, String)

    (7) Get iHealth device controller.

    getAm3Control(String)
    getAm3sControl(String)
    getBp3lControl(String)
    getBp3mControl(String)
    getBp5Control(String)
    getBp7Control(String)
    getHs4Control(String)
    getHs4sControl(String)
    getHs5Control(String)
    getHs5ControlForBt(String)
    getPo3Control(String)

      • connectDevice

        public boolean connectDevice(java.lang.String userName,
                             java.lang.String mac)
        Connection to a valid iHealth device nearby.

        The function may not be return immediately, but if will be completed when a iHealth device is available. A iHealthDevicesCallback.onDeviceConnectionStateChange(java.lang.String, java.lang.String, int, int) callback will be invoked when the connection state changes as a result of this function.

        Requires android.Manifest.permission#BLUETOOTH permission.

        Requires android.Manifest.permission#BLUETOOTH_ADMIN permission.

        Parameters:
        userName - the identification of the user, could be the form of email address or mobile phone
        mac - a valid iHealth device mac
        Returns:
        true, if a iHealth device is connected successfully false, if the user does not have permission to connect this device or the mac is not valid

      • addCallbackFilterForAddress

        public boolean addCallbackFilterForAddress(int clientCallbackId,
                                           java.lang.String... macs)
        Add a or more destination device mac to mathch against.

        If any callback are included in the filter, call is trigged, if not, the callback is ingnored. If the filter methods addCallbackFilterForAddress(int, java.lang.String...) and addCallbackFilterForDeviceType(int, java.lang.String...) are not called, none callback is ingnored.

        Parameters:
        clientCallbackId - This is callback id, calling registerClientCallback(com.ihealth.communication.manager.iHealthDevicesCallback) will return the Id.
        macs - iHealth device address without colon.
        Returns:
        true, if all mac is valid.

      • addCallbackFilterForDeviceType

        public boolean addCallbackFilterForDeviceType(int clientCallbackId,
                                              java.lang.String... deviceTypes)
        * Add a or more destination device type to mathch against.

        If any callback are included in the filter, call is trigged, if not, the callback is ingnored. If the filter methods addCallbackFilterForAddress(int, java.lang.String...) and addCallbackFilterForDeviceType(int, java.lang.String...) are not called, none callback is ingnored.

        Parameters:
        clientCallbackId - This is callback id, calling registerClientCallback(com.ihealth.communication.manager.iHealthDevicesCallback) will return the Id.
        deviceTypes - iHealth device type.
        Returns:
        true, if all mac is valid.

      • startDiscovery

        public void startDiscovery(long type)
        Start discovery valid iHealth device.

        If haven't call stopDiscovery(), the discovery process usually will last for 12 seconds

        If calling connectDevice(java.lang.String, java.lang.String), the discovery process will stop.

        This is an asynchronous call, it will return immediately. When a valid iHealth device is found, Callback iHealthDevicesCallback.onScanDevice(java.lang.String, java.lang.String, int) will be trigged.

        According to Android official document, Device discovery is heavyweight method. When using some iHealth device controller to measure or get historic data, it is not recommended for discovery.

        Parameters:
        type -

        Stop discovery process.
